You took the trope and are doing something with it, but that is 'making' it good rather than it 'being' good.

>>12657954
It is great reading.
Doesn't make the plot device any less overused, though it was less so back in the day. Still, the 'trope' can be easily traced back to fantastical adventure stories in the 1500s and a proper literary historian could likely think of even earlier examples.

Thinking about it, it might have come about as a consequence of the enlightenment period, as the division between 'reality' and 'fantasy' became more prominent.
In really old works there was no division, the protagonist could wander a few miles out of town and encounter giants and dragons, without any break in suspension of disbelief for the reader, the fantastic was part of life.
Later on these elements were pushed to "distant lands", by the industrial era you had to set stories on Mars and these days we have escalated things so far that even alternative dimensions are barely far enough.
So, with the 'fantastic' so far away at this point we need a way to reach it and while " *POOF* You are there! " was quaint for a while some alternatives would be good.

The aimless rambling is over.
